07044nam a22009135i 9789048523573DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20162016ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485235737 a10.1515/97890485235732doi  a(DE-B1597)502885  a(OCoLC)953582360  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1995.9.M45 7aART0570002bisacsh0481pa791qDE-10100aMelodrama After the Tears :bNew Perspectives on the Politics of Victimhood /ced. by Jörg Metelmann, Scott Loren. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b22 color plates, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFilm Culture in Transition00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI. Cultures of Suffering and Cinematic Identities -- tMelodrama and Victimhood: Modern, Political and Militant -- tWhen Is Melodrama “Good”? Mega‑Melodrama and Victimhood -- tMelodrama and War in Hollywood Genre Cinema -- tRace Interactions: Film, Melodrama, and the Ambiguities of Colorism -- tThe Purloined Letter: Ophuls after Cavell -- tII. Modernity and the Melodramatic Self -- tThe Melodrama of the Self -- tRousseau’s Nightmare -- t“Emotional Suffering” as Universal Category? Victimhood and the Collective Imaginary -- tIII. Collective Traumas and National Melodramas -- tIII.1 Legacies of 9/11 -- tIntroduction to W. J. T. Mitchell, “The Abu Ghraib Archive” -- tThe Abu Ghraib Archive -- tThe Melodramatic Style of American Politics -- tTears of Testimony: Glenn Beck and the Conservative Moral Occult -- tIII.2 Holocaust Legacies -- tThe Cultural Construction of the Holocaust Witness as a Melodramatic Hero -- tNation and Emotion: The Competition for Victimhood in Europe -- tPerspectives -- tInterview with Christine Gledhill -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Film Titles -- tIndex of Names -- tFilm Culture in Transition0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMelodrama, it is said, has expanded beyond the borders of genre and fiction to become a pervasive cultural mode. It encompasses distinct signifying practices and interpretive codes for meaning-making that help determine the parameters of identification and subject formation. From the public staging of personal suffering or the psychologization of the self in relation to consumer capitalism, to the emotionalization and sentimentalization of national politics, contributions to this volume address the following question: If melodramatic models of sense-making have become so culturally pervasive and emotionally persuasive, what is the political potential of melodramatic victimhood and where are its political limitations?[-]This volume represents both a condensation and an expansion in the growing field of melodrama studies. It condenses elements of theory on melodrama by bringing into focus what it recognizes to be the locus for subjective identification within melodramatic narratives: the victim. On the other hand, it provides an expansion by going beyond the common methodology of primarily examining fictive works - be they from the stage, the screen or the written word - for their explicit or latent commentary on and connection to the historical contexts within which they are produced. Inspiration for the volume is rooted in a curiosity about melodramatic forms purported to increasingly characterize aspects of both the private and the social sphere in occidental and western-oriented societies.[-]  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aMelodrama, Victimhood, Cultural Studies.1 aAnker, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDecker, Chr